{
  "summary": "The text discusses the story of Elisha being mocked by children who called him 'baldhead', referencing a Biblical narrative. It interprets this incident as a foreshadowing of Christ being mocked by the Jews. The punishment of the children by two bears is likened to the Roman generals Titus and Vespasian executing divine vengeance on the Jews. The passage also draws a parallel between Elisha ascending and Christ being lifted on the cross at Golgotha. It concludes by affirming that all who accepted Christ and were redeemed by his blood became children of God, understanding that he came in the flesh as generated from the heart of the Father. The teachings of this Psalm are believed in the context of the Catholic faith.",
  "keywords": ["Typology", "Vengeance", "Anti-Judaism"]
}
